"The first call for every outrageous, unthinkable and unknown possibility." 

Polina Zakh (@polina__zakh), Creative Director of Russian-American studio Sila Sveta (@silasveta), walks us through what it takes to create their daring, transcendental arena-scale installations for brands like Samsung and Porsche, and 3D visuals for Billie Eilish and Drake.

“As a kid I remember always watching my dad laying underneath a car, the feet sticking out” explains designer Anders Warming (@anders_warming_design). “I always had so much respect for the way he took care of cars.”

Follow Anders’ journey as he works to meticulously restore a car he and his father worked on together in this beautiful video hosted on our channel from our friend @alex___schiller 🟡

node.text:
On a small island off the southern coast of Australia is this bubblegum pink body of water, Lake Hillier. It's been this way for at least three hundred years, discovered by Europeans for the first time in 1802 who noted its distinct colouration.

The hue is thanks to a specific type of algae which is specialised for living in high-salt environments and the chemical produced is actually the exact same that gives the flamingo its signature shade of pink 🦩 • 📸: @dan.mueller

node.text:
Within the soft brutalism of this project by Spanish studio Malu de Miguel (@malu_de_miguel) it’s hard to tell sometimes whether its the fittings or the material’s texture that elevates it beyond its inanimate nature.

The studio elected to cast the concrete walls in chipboard, giving them a more random, fibrous texture. The brickwork meanwhile is as much mortar as it is brick, giving the human touch a chance to define the finished surface. With a mix of hard worn leather and stainless steel, the furniture echoes these industrial materials as well, but nothing feels too machine finished and in that it doesn’t take itself too seriously.

Photos via @malu_de_miguel 
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Over the last 20 years, @9ff_german_engineering has been custom engineering and building parts to make a number of record-breaking Porsches. The 9ff GT9 was a mid-engined creation based on a 997 GT3 with a maximum speed of 437kph - nothing to slouch at. Neither are the numbers from a car nicknamed Salvatore, a 997 Turbo-based platform which pushes 2000hp and is capable of sprinting from 0-300kph in just shy of ten seconds.

These bonkers numbers aside, Jan’s space doesn’t simply focus on smashing records for the sake of it. The car you see above runs a ‘modest’ 1400hp for almost 35,000km without any need to open up the engine. As they say in Cupertino: It just works. Except, at 9ff, it just happens to work at 300kph.

We asked Jan what the next evolution will be, and he pointed to electric powertrains, and you can rest assured that he will be eyeing up the records once again in the coming years.

node.text:
Jan Fatthauer fell in love with Porsche early. After all, it’s hard not to when you grow up in Germany. It led him to study mechanical engineering, specialising in vehicle and engine technology, eventually taking him to jobs at the tuning shops Brabus and RUF. After years at these renowned places, Jan felt the need to give form to his own concepts, having full control over the artistic and engineering visions of projects: his ideas had become too big to ignore.

In 2001, Jan made the leap, creating his own space, @9ff_german_engineering, in Dortmund. It was a pragmatic and deeply emotional decision, basing the workshop in Germany’s biggest metropolitan area, with 18 million people, but most importantly with his wife, Frauke, who was involved in the project from its inception two decades ago.

node.text:
Designed and realised in 1965, this villa in Rossdorf by Jan Lippert is a perfect emblem of how the Bauhaus ideal ultimately survived the early 1900s. Its clean lines and glazed facades are straight out of the Dessau school’s playbook. Although Lippert was never a student there, he did study under its director Ludwig Mies van der Rohe in the mid 1950s after he had left his native Germany for American shores.

The Rossdorf villa is a dead ringer for some of modernism’s fledgling efforts, though naturally it takes on some technological improvements from the interim years. It puts us in mind particularly of Villa Tugendhat, an early Mies van der Rohe construction in the neighbouring Czech Republic and one we’ve previously covered.

Of course there’s plenty of design commentary to be made here but more importantly, it represents a homecoming of progressive design ideals that had been so unnecessarily ostracised in the past. Jan Lippert may have remained in Illinois, had a latent appetite for the Bauhaus not reemerged across the Atlantic. In hindsight, nobody could remember just what was so threatening about houses of steel and glass.

Photos by @gregorzoyzoyla
